All right.

00:15:08.676 --> 00:15:09.686 A:middle
So there's one more thing that

00:15:09.686 --> 00:15:12.016 A:middle
I'd like to take a look at, and

00:15:12.466 --> 00:15:13.696 A:middle
that's a performance problem

00:15:13.996 --> 00:15:15.736 A:middle
that my colleague was pointing

00:15:15.736 --> 00:15:15.866 A:middle
out.

00:15:15.866 --> 00:15:17.476 A:middle
We were tapping around with the

00:15:17.476 --> 00:15:18.706 A:middle
SolarSystem and they noticed

00:15:19.306 --> 00:15:20.636 A:middle
when they tapped on Jupiter,

00:15:21.896 --> 00:15:23.446 A:middle
there's a bit of a lag.

00:15:23.616 --> 00:15:25.376 A:middle
The camera doesn't show it

00:15:25.376 --> 00:15:26.846 A:middle
really well, but you can kind of

00:15:26.846 --> 00:15:28.496 A:middle
see a pause and, you know,

00:15:28.706 --> 00:15:31.976 A:middle
that's impacting battery life

00:15:32.016 --> 00:15:32.626 A:middle
and we just kind of want to take

00:15:32.656 --> 00:15:33.496 A:middle
a look and see if we can figure

00:15:33.526 --> 00:15:33.976 A:middle
out what's going on.

00:15:38.046 --> 00:15:38.806 A:middle
So I'm going to go to the Energy

00:15:38.806 --> 00:15:39.406 A:middle
Impact Gauge.

00:15:39.476 --> 00:15:40.286 A:middle
Sure enough it's high.

00:15:40.286 --> 00:15:41.496 A:middle
You'll notice that this has been

00:15:41.496 --> 00:15:42.896 A:middle
redesigned in Xcode 9 to give

00:15:42.896 --> 00:15:44.466 A:middle
you a much better look at

00:15:44.466 --> 00:15:46.576 A:middle
exactly where your energy is

00:15:46.576 --> 00:15:47.746 A:middle
being consumed by your app.

00:15:47.746 --> 00:15:50.176 A:middle
So in this case we've got the

00:15:50.176 --> 00:15:51.826 A:middle
CPU, which I think is probably

00:15:51.826 --> 00:15:53.066 A:middle
taking a little bit more than it

00:15:53.066 --> 00:15:55.736 A:middle
should for a GPU-oriented app,

00:15:55.926 --> 00:15:57.606 A:middle
and it goes up every time I

00:15:57.606 --> 00:15:58.186 A:middle
touch that.

00:15:58.506 --> 00:16:00.956 A:middle
So what do we do when we need to

00:16:00.956 --> 00:16:02.116 A:middle
dig deeper into performance

00:16:02.116 --> 00:16:02.546 A:middle
problems?

00:16:02.756 --> 00:16:03.736 A:middle
Well, we go into Instruments.

00:16:04.136 --> 00:16:05.386 A:middle
Now, some of you may not know

00:16:05.386 --> 00:16:06.556 A:middle
this, but there's a really cool

00:16:06.556 --> 00:16:07.416 A:middle
feature in Xcode.

00:16:07.806 --> 00:16:08.906 A:middle
If you've ever had to like --

00:16:10.236 --> 00:16:11.296 A:middle
you know, you're debugging a bug

00:16:11.296 --> 00:16:12.236 A:middle
and you're like, oh, man,

00:16:12.236 --> 00:16:13.276 A:middle
there's a performance problem,

00:16:13.556 --> 00:16:15.136 A:middle
all right, let me, you know, go

00:16:15.136 --> 00:16:16.126 A:middle
to Instruments and start it

00:16:16.126 --> 00:16:17.386 A:middle
again, you don't have to do

00:16:17.386 --> 00:16:17.646 A:middle
that.

00:16:17.646 --> 00:16:18.706 A:middle
I'm going to click the Time

00:16:18.706 --> 00:16:20.236 A:middle
Profile button and this is going

00:16:20.236 --> 00:16:21.896 A:middle
to transfer the debug session to

00:16:21.896 --> 00:16:22.986 A:middle
Instruments and keep the app

00:16:23.026 --> 00:16:23.386 A:middle
going.

00:16:23.676 --> 00:16:24.816 A:middle
This is great if you've got an

00:16:24.816 --> 00:16:26.296 A:middle
app in state and you need to

00:16:26.296 --> 00:16:27.466 A:middle
jump over to Instruments and see

00:16:27.466 --> 00:16:28.236 A:middle
what's going on.

00:16:28.446 --> 00:16:29.886 A:middle
So we've started Instruments.

00:16:29.886 --> 00:16:30.796 A:middle
I'm going to move the window

00:16:30.796 --> 00:16:31.656 A:middle
over, give us a little bit of a

00:16:31.656 --> 00:16:31.976 A:middle
better view.

00:16:36.376 --> 00:16:38.776 A:middle
And we see that we are in the

00:16:38.806 --> 00:16:40.406 A:middle
Instruments default strategy,

00:16:40.406 --> 00:16:41.676 A:middle
which just says the CPU Usage

00:16:41.746 --> 00:16:43.966 A:middle
and the Life Cycle, but new in

00:16:43.966 --> 00:16:45.476 A:middle
Instruments for Xcode 9 is this

00:16:45.476 --> 00:16:46.236 A:middle
All strategy.

00:16:46.486 --> 00:16:47.616 A:middle
So this is the time profile

00:16:47.616 --> 00:16:49.466 A:middle
instrument, but if I click All,

00:16:49.666 --> 00:16:52.206 A:middle
I see all of the threads and the

00:16:52.206 --> 00:16:54.006 A:middle
cores and I get the big picture

00:16:54.556 --> 00:16:55.006 A:middle
of the app.

00:16:55.226 --> 00:16:55.976 A:middle
Really, really useful.

00:16:55.976 --> 00:16:57.226 A:middle
So let's see if we can reproduce

00:16:57.226 --> 00:16:57.976 A:middle
the problem.

00:16:58.516 --> 00:17:03.726 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:17:04.226 --> 00:17:04.976 A:middle
Here we go.

00:17:09.266 --> 00:17:09.556 A:middle
All right.

00:17:09.556 --> 00:17:10.716 A:middle
So we've clearly seen that

00:17:10.716 --> 00:17:11.326 A:middle
there's an issue.

00:17:12.066 --> 00:17:13.156 A:middle
We've got this spike here.

00:17:13.406 --> 00:17:15.876 A:middle
Now, sometimes you want to just

00:17:15.876 --> 00:17:17.376 A:middle
dig directly into that and look

00:17:17.376 --> 00:17:18.246 A:middle
at the call stacks, but

00:17:18.246 --> 00:17:19.536 A:middle
sometimes what you want to do is

00:17:19.536 --> 00:17:22.546 A:middle
correlate that spike to what CPU

00:17:22.546 --> 00:17:26.296 A:middle
it's on, other threads, and you

00:17:26.296 --> 00:17:27.196 A:middle
know how to do that, right, you

00:17:27.196 --> 00:17:28.266 A:middle
just scroll, back it up, and you

00:17:28.266 --> 00:17:29.386 A:middle
look and you see, oh, is there

00:17:29.386 --> 00:17:31.016 A:middle
another one, well, I'm not sure.

00:17:31.396 --> 00:17:33.216 A:middle
Well, for Instruments in Xcode 9

00:17:33.246 --> 00:17:34.296 A:middle
there is a much better way.

00:17:34.786 --> 00:17:36.036 A:middle
I'm going to pin this track,

00:17:36.406 --> 00:17:38.136 A:middle
right, and pinning the track

00:17:39.036 --> 00:17:40.486 A:middle
actually puts a copy of that

00:17:40.486 --> 00:17:41.916 A:middle
track at the bottom and it's

00:17:41.916 --> 00:17:42.276 A:middle
fixed.

00:17:42.276 --> 00:17:44.126 A:middle
So now I can scroll up and down

00:17:44.316 --> 00:17:46.876 A:middle
and I can correlate what other

00:17:47.096 --> 00:17:48.246 A:middle
tracks are sharing that

00:17:48.666 --> 00:17:49.976 A:middle
performance characteristic

00:17:50.016 --> 00:17:50.691 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:17:50.691 --> 00:17:51.366 A:middle
.

00:17:51.366 --> 00:17:52.666 A:middle
Yeah, it's really, really cool.

00:17:54.066 --> 00:17:55.806 A:middle
And not only can you just see

00:17:55.806 --> 00:17:57.476 A:middle
the spikes, but I think it's

00:17:57.476 --> 00:17:58.896 A:middle
also important to know what's

00:17:58.896 --> 00:17:59.546 A:middle
not happening.

00:17:59.636 --> 00:18:01.236 A:middle
So being able to see that all of

00:18:01.236 --> 00:18:02.376 A:middle
these are not correlated

00:18:02.776 --> 00:18:03.746 A:middle
obviously gives you information

00:18:03.746 --> 00:18:03.976 A:middle
as well.

00:18:10.056 --> 00:18:11.816 A:middle
Okay. So what we've just seen

00:18:12.046 --> 00:18:16.316 A:middle
are a few things that you can do

00:18:16.606 --> 00:18:17.656 A:middle
with wireless development in

00:18:17.656 --> 00:18:18.166 A:middle
Xcode 9.

00:18:20.876 --> 00:18:22.666 A:middle
Don't need that.

00:18:22.666 --> 00:18:25.086 A:middle
So this just scratches the

00:18:25.086 --> 00:18:26.626 A:middle
surface because, as Chris said,

00:18:26.626 --> 00:18:28.086 A:middle
there's lots of times,

00:18:28.156 --> 00:18:30.186 A:middle
especially today, when the apps

00:18:30.186 --> 00:18:32.526 A:middle
we're developing, they are not

00:18:32.966 --> 00:18:35.136 A:middle
you sitting down and consuming

00:18:35.136 --> 00:18:36.986 A:middle
content while you're on the bus.

00:18:37.066 --> 00:18:38.146 A:middle
Those apps still exist, of

00:18:38.146 --> 00:18:40.016 A:middle
course, but more and more of our

00:18:40.016 --> 00:18:41.546 A:middle
apps are physical, they're

00:18:41.546 --> 00:18:42.756 A:middle
interacting in the real world,

00:18:43.116 --> 00:18:45.456 A:middle
and sometimes you get reports

00:18:45.456 --> 00:18:46.346 A:middle
and you want to reproduce

00:18:46.346 --> 00:18:47.806 A:middle
problems that you can only

00:18:47.806 --> 00:18:49.566 A:middle
reproduce in the real world.

00:18:49.876 --> 00:18:51.116 A:middle
Sometimes you have performance

00:18:51.116 --> 00:18:52.366 A:middle
problems where you need a tool

00:18:52.366 --> 00:18:53.826 A:middle
like Instruments to really dig

00:18:53.826 --> 00:18:55.736 A:middle
deep into your performance and

00:18:55.736 --> 00:18:57.096 A:middle
you want to do that in the real

00:18:57.096 --> 00:18:57.486 A:middle
world.

00:18:57.626 --> 00:18:59.116 A:middle
And with wireless development

00:18:59.166 --> 00:18:59.436 A:middle
you can.

00:18:59.436 --> 00:19:00.236 A:middle
And with that, I'd like to hand

00:19:00.236 --> 00:19:00.956 A:middle
it back to Chris.

00:19:01.516 --> 00:19:07.786 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:19:08.286 --> 00:19:08.846 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Thanks, Breckin.

00:19:09.256 --> 00:19:10.086 A:middle
What a fun demo.

00:19:10.436 --> 00:19:11.736 A:middle
All right.

00:19:11.736 --> 00:19:13.016 A:middle
I'd like to move on to talking

00:19:13.016 --> 00:19:15.016 A:middle
about enhancements we've made in

00:19:15.016 --> 00:19:15.976 A:middle
Xcode for working with

00:19:15.976 --> 00:19:16.676 A:middle
breakpoints.

00:19:17.136 --> 00:19:19.696 A:middle
Some of you may not know, but in

00:19:19.696 --> 00:19:21.266 A:middle
Xcode breakpoints have a lot of

00:19:21.266 --> 00:19:22.056 A:middle
flexibility.

00:19:22.706 --> 00:19:23.736 A:middle
There are options that you can

00:19:23.736 --> 00:19:25.016 A:middle
set to customize the way that

00:19:25.016 --> 00:19:25.586 A:middle
they behave.

00:19:26.226 --> 00:19:28.096 A:middle
To do this just double click on

00:19:28.096 --> 00:19:29.856 A:middle
a breakpoint and you'll see the

00:19:29.856 --> 00:19:31.156 A:middle
Breakpoint Editor popover.

00:19:31.716 --> 00:19:33.626 A:middle
From here you can set options

00:19:33.626 --> 00:19:35.776 A:middle
such as defining a condition so

00:19:36.286 --> 00:19:37.626 A:middle
the breakpoint will only trigger

00:19:37.626 --> 00:19:38.836 A:middle
if that condition evaluates

00:19:38.836 --> 00:19:40.456 A:middle
true; and you can define

00:19:40.836 --> 00:19:42.396 A:middle
breakpoint actions, such as

00:19:42.396 --> 00:19:43.756 A:middle
logging variables, executing

00:19:43.756 --> 00:19:45.286 A:middle
debugger commands for you and

00:19:45.346 --> 00:19:46.106 A:middle
playing sounds.

00:19:46.566 --> 00:19:47.796 A:middle
Now, these options have been in

00:19:47.796 --> 00:19:49.826 A:middle
Xcode for some time, but over

00:19:49.826 --> 00:19:51.076 A:middle
the past year the team have been

00:19:51.076 --> 00:19:52.206 A:middle
making some enhancements to the

00:19:52.206 --> 00:19:53.916 A:middle
UI to make them easier to work

00:19:53.916 --> 00:19:54.056 A:middle
with.

00:19:55.016 --> 00:19:56.946 A:middle
The first of these, we've added

00:19:56.946 --> 00:19:57.776 A:middle
code completion to all the

00:19:57.846 --> 00:19:58.976 A:middle
Breakpoint Editor text fields.

00:19:59.516 --> 00:20:05.586 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:20:06.086 --> 00:20:07.246 A:middle
So now in the Breakpoint Editor,

00:20:07.576 --> 00:20:10.766 A:middle
when editing expressions in the

00:20:10.766 --> 00:20:12.166 A:middle
condition field and the

00:20:12.166 --> 00:20:13.616 A:middle
breakpoint action fields, you

00:20:13.616 --> 00:20:14.986 A:middle
get full code completion, the

00:20:14.986 --> 00:20:16.536 A:middle
same as you'd expect from the

00:20:16.536 --> 00:20:18.476 A:middle
Source Editor and the Debugger

00:20:18.476 --> 00:20:18.956 A:middle
Console.

00:20:19.526 --> 00:20:21.656 A:middle
The next thing we wanted to do

00:20:21.656 --> 00:20:23.366 A:middle
was make finding breakpoints

00:20:23.366 --> 00:20:25.196 A:middle
with options set on them much

00:20:25.196 --> 00:20:27.786 A:middle
easier, so in Xcode 9, for any

00:20:27.786 --> 00:20:29.216 A:middle
breakpoints that have options

00:20:29.216 --> 00:20:30.196 A:middle
set on them, you'll see this

00:20:30.196 --> 00:20:31.236 A:middle
alternate indicator with a

00:20:31.236 --> 00:20:31.976 A:middle
triangle at the end.

00:20:32.516 --> 00:20:36.706 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:20:37.206 --> 00:20:38.936 A:middle
So this indicates that that

00:20:38.936 --> 00:20:40.506 A:middle
breakpoint has one or more

00:20:40.506 --> 00:20:41.986 A:middle
options set on it.

00:20:41.986 --> 00:20:43.776 A:middle
This makes it really easy to see

00:20:43.776 --> 00:20:45.186 A:middle
at a glance, when looking at

00:20:45.406 --> 00:20:46.726 A:middle
either the Breakpoint Navigator

00:20:47.036 --> 00:20:48.546 A:middle
or the Source Editor, which of

00:20:48.546 --> 00:20:49.886 A:middle
those breakpoints have options

00:20:49.886 --> 00:20:51.246 A:middle
set on them.

00:20:51.686 --> 00:20:53.326 A:middle
Furthermore, just mouse over the

00:20:53.326 --> 00:20:54.756 A:middle
breakpoint and a tooltip will

00:20:54.756 --> 00:20:55.916 A:middle
show you a summary of the

00:20:55.916 --> 00:20:56.996 A:middle
options that have been set on

00:20:56.996 --> 00:20:57.536 A:middle
the breakpoint.

00:20:58.046 --> 00:20:59.006 A:middle
This should make finding the

00:20:59.006 --> 00:21:00.036 A:middle
breakpoint you're looking for

00:21:00.236 --> 00:21:00.856 A:middle
much easier.

00:21:01.586 --> 00:21:02.516 A:middle
And speaking of finding

00:21:02.516 --> 00:21:04.656 A:middle
breakpoints, we've also enhanced

00:21:04.836 --> 00:21:06.246 A:middle
the Breakpoint Navigator filter

00:21:06.246 --> 00:21:08.296 A:middle
field by adding deep filtering.

00:21:08.746 --> 00:21:10.426 A:middle
This means that it now searches

00:21:10.716 --> 00:21:12.726 A:middle
your query across all of the

00:21:12.726 --> 00:21:13.936 A:middle
text fields in the Breakpoint

00:21:13.936 --> 00:21:14.206 A:middle
Editor.

00:21:14.596 --> 00:21:15.676 A:middle
So you can match on condition

00:21:15.676 --> 00:21:16.906 A:middle
fields and any of the action

00:21:16.906 --> 00:21:18.266 A:middle
fields and expressions that

00:21:18.266 --> 00:21:19.186 A:middle
you've set in those.

00:21:20.136 --> 00:21:21.856 A:middle
This makes finding breakpoints

00:21:22.056 --> 00:21:23.266 A:middle
much more powerful and much

00:21:23.266 --> 00:21:24.586 A:middle
easier in the Breakpoint

00:21:24.636 --> 00:21:25.076 A:middle
Navigator.

00:21:26.446 --> 00:21:27.396 A:middle
So if you haven't been using

00:21:27.396 --> 00:21:28.676 A:middle
breakpoint options, give them a

00:21:28.676 --> 00:21:28.946 A:middle
try.

00:21:28.946 --> 00:21:29.756 A:middle
They can add a lot of

00:21:29.956 --> 00:21:31.576 A:middle
flexibility and customization to

00:21:31.576 --> 00:21:32.526 A:middle
your debugging workflow, and now

00:21:32.526 --> 00:21:32.976 A:middle
they're easier to use.

00:21:37.216 --> 00:21:38.676 A:middle
I'd like to move on to talking

00:21:38.676 --> 00:21:40.136 A:middle
about user interface debugging.

00:21:41.426 --> 00:21:43.296 A:middle
Now, when building UI, View

00:21:43.296 --> 00:21:44.136 A:middle
Controller is playing an

00:21:44.136 --> 00:21:47.086 A:middle
important role in how you

00:21:47.086 --> 00:21:48.246 A:middle
structure your code and your

00:21:48.246 --> 00:21:49.046 A:middle
storyboards.

00:21:49.886 --> 00:21:51.986 A:middle
View controllers manage and lay

00:21:51.986 --> 00:21:53.236 A:middle
out portions of the view tree

00:21:53.686 --> 00:21:55.486 A:middle
and are responsible for handling

00:21:55.486 --> 00:21:56.816 A:middle
transitions between screens.

00:21:57.706 --> 00:21:58.796 A:middle
So when debugging your UI,

00:21:58.796 --> 00:22:00.046 A:middle
wouldn't it be great to be able

00:22:00.046 --> 00:22:01.576 A:middle
to navigate that view hierarchy

00:22:01.846 --> 00:22:03.646 A:middle
by focusing on the View

00:22:03.646 --> 00:22:05.476 A:middle
Controller structure and to also

00:22:05.476 --> 00:22:06.966 A:middle
be able to find view controllers

00:22:07.146 --> 00:22:08.606 A:middle
that are responsible for parts

00:22:08.606 --> 00:22:09.156 A:middle
of the view tree.

00:22:10.156 --> 00:22:11.906 A:middle
We thought so, too, so in Xcode

00:22:11.906 --> 00:22:13.516 A:middle
9 view controllers are now

00:22:13.516 --> 00:22:15.286 A:middle
included as part of the view

00:22:15.286 --> 00:22:15.976 A:middle
hierarchy when debugging.

00:22:16.516 --> 00:22:21.306 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:22:21.806 --> 00:22:22.956 A:middle
Inspect your view hierarchy like

00:22:22.996 --> 00:22:24.256 A:middle
you always have been, but now

00:22:24.256 --> 00:22:25.736 A:middle
you can expect to find View

00:22:25.736 --> 00:22:27.376 A:middle
controllers in the Debug

00:22:27.376 --> 00:22:29.436 A:middle
Navigator inserted as parents of

00:22:29.436 --> 00:22:30.656 A:middle
the views that they manage.

00:22:31.386 --> 00:22:32.866 A:middle
This makes it really easy to

00:22:32.866 --> 00:22:34.686 A:middle
navigate the view hierarchy by

00:22:34.686 --> 00:22:36.466 A:middle
first focusing on the high-level

00:22:36.626 --> 00:22:38.226 A:middle
View Controller structure to

00:22:38.226 --> 00:22:39.426 A:middle
find the area of the view tree

00:22:39.426 --> 00:22:40.866 A:middle
that you're looking to debug and

00:22:40.866 --> 00:22:42.436 A:middle
then focusing in on individual

00:22:42.436 --> 00:22:42.916 A:middle
views.

00:22:43.406 --> 00:22:45.706 A:middle
View controllers are represented

00:22:45.706 --> 00:22:47.866 A:middle
visually in the Canvas as well.

00:22:48.776 --> 00:22:50.746 A:middle
Xcode renders banners for View

00:22:50.746 --> 00:22:52.046 A:middle
controllers above the views that

00:22:52.046 --> 00:22:52.586 A:middle
they manage.

00:22:53.316 --> 00:22:55.296 A:middle
This is great for visualizing

00:22:55.386 --> 00:22:56.656 A:middle
the View Controller boundaries

00:22:56.656 --> 00:22:58.316 A:middle
in that view tree and makes it

00:22:58.316 --> 00:22:59.836 A:middle
much easier to find the view

00:22:59.836 --> 00:23:01.196 A:middle
controllers responsible for a

00:23:01.196 --> 00:23:03.976 A:middle
particular view.

00:23:04.236 --> 00:23:05.556 A:middle
Select a View Controller and

00:23:05.556 --> 00:23:06.956 A:middle
you'll see its properties in the

00:23:06.956 --> 00:23:08.266 A:middle
Inspectors, and this helps you

00:23:08.266 --> 00:23:09.356 A:middle
when you're debugging View

00:23:09.356 --> 00:23:10.666 A:middle
Controller specific issues.

00:23:11.246 --> 00:23:12.806 A:middle
It includes the View Controller

00:23:12.806 --> 00:23:14.126 A:middle
parent and child relationships,

00:23:14.606 --> 00:23:16.076 A:middle
which is great for debugging

00:23:16.076 --> 00:23:17.146 A:middle
View Controller containment

00:23:17.146 --> 00:23:17.666 A:middle
issues.

00:23:19.236 --> 00:23:20.276 A:middle
So now that view controllers are

00:23:20.276 --> 00:23:21.676 A:middle
included as part of the view

00:23:21.676 --> 00:23:23.096 A:middle
hierarchy when debugging, it

00:23:23.096 --> 00:23:24.506 A:middle
makes it much easier to navigate

00:23:24.506 --> 00:23:26.246 A:middle
that hierarchy and to help you

00:23:26.246 --> 00:23:28.166 A:middle
to solve View Controller-related

00:23:28.166 --> 00:23:28.666 A:middle
issues.

00:23:29.206 --> 00:23:32.346 A:middle
Now, not all user interfaces are

00:23:32.346 --> 00:23:34.296 A:middle
built using UIKit and AppKit.

00:23:35.376 --> 00:23:37.336 A:middle
Some designs may require custom

00:23:37.336 --> 00:23:40.786 A:middle
UI with rich interactions and

00:23:40.786 --> 00:23:41.666 A:middle
custom layouts.

00:23:42.166 --> 00:23:44.146 A:middle
One option to do this is using

00:23:44.146 --> 00:23:44.716 A:middle
SpriteKit.

00:23:46.336 --> 00:23:47.796 A:middle
SpriteKit is a 2D graphics

00:23:47.796 --> 00:23:48.866 A:middle
framework and it's available

00:23:48.866 --> 00:23:50.416 A:middle
across all of Apple's platforms.

00:23:50.936 --> 00:23:52.276 A:middle
It's great for building games,

00:23:52.276 --> 00:23:52.776 A:middle
of course.

00:23:52.836 --> 00:23:53.876 A:middle
It's also great for building

00:23:53.876 --> 00:23:54.936 A:middle
this kind of custom UI.

00:23:54.936 --> 00:23:57.576 A:middle
So we wanted to provide the same

00:23:57.576 --> 00:23:58.866 A:middle
kind of visual debugging tool

00:23:58.866 --> 00:24:00.746 A:middle
for SpriteKit developers that we

00:24:00.746 --> 00:24:02.166 A:middle
provide for developers using

00:24:02.166 --> 00:24:03.026 A:middle
UIKit and AppKit.

00:24:03.826 --> 00:24:04.756 A:middle
So I'm pleased to announce that

00:24:04.756 --> 00:24:08.046 A:middle
in Xcode 9 SpriteKit is now a

00:24:08.046 --> 00:24:10.216 A:middle
first-class citizen in the View

00:24:10.216 --> 00:24:10.516 A:middle
Debugger.

00:24:12.396 --> 00:24:14.286 A:middle
When inspecting your view

00:24:14.286 --> 00:24:16.856 A:middle
hierarchy and Xcode finds a

00:24:16.856 --> 00:24:18.346 A:middle
SpriteKit view, it will

00:24:18.346 --> 00:24:19.446 A:middle
automatically snapshot the

00:24:19.446 --> 00:24:20.966 A:middle
SpriteKit scene hosted by that

00:24:20.966 --> 00:24:22.186 A:middle
view and bring that into the

00:24:22.186 --> 00:24:22.486 A:middle
debugger.

00:24:23.346 --> 00:24:25.196 A:middle
So now you'll see Sprites

00:24:25.196 --> 00:24:26.996 A:middle
rendered in the exploded 3D

00:24:26.996 --> 00:24:28.946 A:middle
visualization, along with all

00:24:28.946 --> 00:24:30.046 A:middle
the views in the hierarchy.

00:24:31.436 --> 00:24:33.316 A:middle
This is great for debugging

00:24:33.506 --> 00:24:34.396 A:middle
Sprite layout.

00:24:35.186 --> 00:24:36.676 A:middle
Also really handy for debugging

00:24:36.676 --> 00:24:38.036 A:middle
Sprite layout alongside View

00:24:38.036 --> 00:24:39.346 A:middle
layout for those projects where

00:24:39.346 --> 00:24:40.456 A:middle
you'd like to mix and match

00:24:40.456 --> 00:24:41.856 A:middle
Sprites and views for custom UI.

00:24:46.116 --> 00:24:47.256 A:middle
In the Debug Navigator you'll

00:24:47.256 --> 00:24:48.836 A:middle
see an entry for the SpriteKit

00:24:48.836 --> 00:24:50.306 A:middle
scene as a child of the view

00:24:50.306 --> 00:24:52.356 A:middle
that hosts it, and below that

00:24:52.356 --> 00:24:53.886 A:middle
scene you'll see all of the

00:24:53.886 --> 00:24:55.886 A:middle
SpriteKit nodes that are in that

00:24:55.886 --> 00:24:56.716 A:middle
scene at runtime.

00:24:57.476 --> 00:25:00.506 A:middle
Select a SpriteKit node and you

00:25:00.506 --> 00:25:02.846 A:middle
can debug that by looking at the

00:25:02.846 --> 00:25:03.476 A:middle
Inspectors.

00:25:04.846 --> 00:25:06.366 A:middle
So now SpriteKit developers have

00:25:06.366 --> 00:25:07.986 A:middle
a visual tool for debugging

00:25:07.986 --> 00:25:08.796 A:middle
their SpriteKit scenes at

00:25:08.796 --> 00:25:08.976 A:middle
runtime.

00:25:09.516 --> 00:25:16.376 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:25:16.876 --> 00:25:17.976 A:middle
But we didn't want to stop at

00:25:19.776 --> 00:25:21.936 A:middle
Sprites. SceneKit is a 3D

00:25:21.936 --> 00:25:22.726 A:middle
graphics framework.

00:25:23.156 --> 00:25:24.406 A:middle
It's great for building rich 3D

00:25:24.406 --> 00:25:26.096 A:middle
worlds and 3D games, as well as

00:25:26.096 --> 00:25:28.216 A:middle
custom 3D UI, so we wanted to

00:25:28.216 --> 00:25:30.166 A:middle
also provide a visual tool for

00:25:30.166 --> 00:25:33.136 A:middle
SceneKit developers, and so we

00:25:33.136 --> 00:25:33.396 A:middle
did.

00:25:33.996 --> 00:25:35.496 A:middle
SceneKit is now included as part

00:25:35.496 --> 00:25:37.046 A:middle
of the View Debugging Workflow.

00:25:37.966 --> 00:25:39.596 A:middle
When Xcode is inspecting a View

00:25:39.596 --> 00:25:40.746 A:middle
hierarchy that contains a

00:25:40.746 --> 00:25:42.656 A:middle
SceneKit view, it will snapshot

00:25:42.656 --> 00:25:44.036 A:middle
the SceneKit scene hosted by

00:25:44.036 --> 00:25:46.096 A:middle
that view and bring that in to

00:25:46.096 --> 00:25:46.926 A:middle
the debugger.

00:25:47.256 --> 00:25:50.866 A:middle
In the Debug Navigator you'll

00:25:50.866 --> 00:25:53.366 A:middle
see an entry for the SceneKit

00:25:53.366 --> 00:25:55.786 A:middle
scene as a child of the view

00:25:55.786 --> 00:25:56.386 A:middle
that hosts it.

00:25:57.126 --> 00:25:58.636 A:middle
But you may notice a difference

00:25:58.636 --> 00:25:59.696 A:middle
here, compared to the SpriteKit

00:25:59.696 --> 00:26:00.646 A:middle
example I just showed.

00:26:01.666 --> 00:26:04.136 A:middle
That SceneKit scene has no child

00:26:04.136 --> 00:26:04.626 A:middle
elements.

00:26:04.826 --> 00:26:06.566 A:middle
Where are all the SceneKit scene

00:26:06.566 --> 00:26:07.016 A:middle
nodes.

00:26:07.776 --> 00:26:10.366 A:middle
Also notice that in the Canvas

00:26:10.436 --> 00:26:11.956 A:middle
the 3D scene is just being

00:26:11.956 --> 00:26:12.996 A:middle
represented by a flattened

00:26:12.996 --> 00:26:13.516 A:middle
snapshot.

00:26:16.196 --> 00:26:17.426 A:middle
So why is this?

00:26:18.106 --> 00:26:20.746 A:middle
Well, to make 2D views in

00:26:20.746 --> 00:26:22.526 A:middle
Sprites explorable, Xcode

00:26:22.526 --> 00:26:24.066 A:middle
explodes them out in 3D.

00:26:24.576 --> 00:26:25.716 A:middle
But what should it do with 3D

00:26:25.716 --> 00:26:26.116 A:middle
content?

00:26:27.526 --> 00:26:28.796 A:middle
Well, we explored the latest

00:26:28.796 --> 00:26:30.096 A:middle
advances in 4D debugging

00:26:30.096 --> 00:26:31.146 A:middle
technology, but after some

00:26:31.146 --> 00:26:32.446 A:middle
accidents in the lab we thought

00:26:32.446 --> 00:26:34.276 A:middle
there must be an easier way, and

00:26:34.276 --> 00:26:34.606 A:middle
there was.

00:26:35.026 --> 00:26:36.116 A:middle
We already have a really

00:26:36.116 --> 00:26:37.866 A:middle
powerful 3D editor built right

00:26:37.866 --> 00:26:40.466 A:middle
into Xcode so we integrated the

00:26:40.466 --> 00:26:41.946 A:middle
SceneKit Editor with the View

00:26:41.946 --> 00:26:42.736 A:middle
Debugging Workflow.

00:26:43.316 --> 00:26:45.106 A:middle
Now just select a SceneKit scene

00:26:45.106 --> 00:26:46.866 A:middle
in the Debug Navigator and Xcode

00:26:46.866 --> 00:26:49.086 A:middle
will open the SceneKit Editor in

00:26:49.386 --> 00:26:50.556 A:middle
runtime debugging mode,

00:26:51.036 --> 00:26:53.016 A:middle
containing a snapshot of your 3D

00:26:53.016 --> 00:26:54.216 A:middle
scene from the runtime.

00:26:55.456 --> 00:26:56.426 A:middle
Now -- [applause] it's pretty

00:26:56.606 --> 00:26:56.716 A:middle
good.

00:26:57.516 --> 00:26:59.656 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:27:00.156 --> 00:27:01.576 A:middle
So now you can use all the same

00:27:01.576 --> 00:27:02.586 A:middle
tools you're already familiar

00:27:02.586 --> 00:27:05.646 A:middle
with when creating a 3D scene to

00:27:05.646 --> 00:27:07.436 A:middle
inspect and debug that 3D scene.

00:27:08.846 --> 00:27:11.026 A:middle
You can move cameras around or

00:27:11.026 --> 00:27:12.656 A:middle
select alternate cameras.

00:27:13.006 --> 00:27:14.246 A:middle
You can zoom right out to get a

00:27:14.246 --> 00:27:15.706 A:middle
big picture view of that entire

00:27:15.706 --> 00:27:17.866 A:middle
scene, and you can visualize

00:27:18.226 --> 00:27:19.486 A:middle
objects in the scene that aren't

00:27:19.486 --> 00:27:21.016 A:middle
normally visible, like cameras

00:27:21.016 --> 00:27:24.066 A:middle
and view frustums and lights and

00:27:24.066 --> 00:27:25.286 A:middle
the light position and

00:27:25.286 --> 00:27:25.736 A:middle
direction.

00:27:26.666 --> 00:27:28.356 A:middle
You can explore the entire scene

00:27:28.356 --> 00:27:29.596 A:middle
graph in the outline view on the

00:27:29.596 --> 00:27:32.486 A:middle
left and you can select objects

00:27:32.546 --> 00:27:35.036 A:middle
in that 3D scene so you can hide

00:27:35.036 --> 00:27:36.436 A:middle
them or move them around to get

00:27:36.436 --> 00:27:37.506 A:middle
at objects that may be behind

00:27:37.506 --> 00:27:37.636 A:middle
them.

00:27:38.076 --> 00:27:39.136 A:middle
In fact, you can make any

00:27:39.136 --> 00:27:40.956 A:middle
modifications to that scene

00:27:41.186 --> 00:27:42.656 A:middle
using either the Canvas or the

00:27:42.656 --> 00:27:43.776 A:middle
Inspectors, which are all fully

00:27:43.776 --> 00:27:45.376 A:middle
operational, safe in the

00:27:45.376 --> 00:27:46.196 A:middle
knowledge that you won't be

00:27:46.196 --> 00:27:47.176 A:middle
affecting your runtime.

00:27:47.626 --> 00:27:48.836 A:middle
You'll just been modifying an

00:27:48.836 --> 00:27:49.766 A:middle
in-memory snapshot.

00:27:50.676 --> 00:27:51.726 A:middle
And if you'd like to save a copy

00:27:51.726 --> 00:27:53.376 A:middle
of that snapshot, that's easy,

00:27:53.376 --> 00:27:53.666 A:middle
too.

00:27:53.756 --> 00:27:55.176 A:middle
You can just export that out to

00:27:55.176 --> 00:27:57.406 A:middle
a SceneKit or a .dae file to

00:27:57.406 --> 00:27:58.476 A:middle
access at a later time.

00:27:59.386 --> 00:28:01.206 A:middle
So now SceneKit developers have

00:28:01.206 --> 00:28:02.736 A:middle
a visual debugging tool for

00:28:02.736 --> 00:28:04.606 A:middle
debugging their SceneKit scenes

00:28:04.606 --> 00:28:04.976 A:middle
at runtime.

00:28:05.516 --> 00:28:12.096 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:28:12.596 --> 00:28:13.946 A:middle
So these are the enhancements

00:28:13.946 --> 00:28:16.086 A:middle
we've made for View debugging in

00:28:16.116 --> 00:28:16.776 A:middle
Xcode 9.

00:28:17.236 --> 00:28:18.136 A:middle
We've added View Controller

00:28:18.136 --> 00:28:20.026 A:middle
debugging, SpriteKit and

00:28:20.096 --> 00:28:20.926 A:middle
SceneKit debugging.

00:28:21.796 --> 00:28:22.706 A:middle
To take advantage of these

00:28:22.706 --> 00:28:24.186 A:middle
features your project just needs

00:28:24.186 --> 00:28:26.526 A:middle
to be running on one of the OS

00:28:26.526 --> 00:28:28.456 A:middle
releases from this week; iOS 11,

00:28:28.876 --> 00:28:30.976 A:middle
tvOS 11 or macOS High Sierra.

00:28:35.376 --> 00:28:36.186 A:middle
Now, I had mentioned that

00:28:36.396 --> 00:28:37.376 A:middle
graphics frameworks like

00:28:37.566 --> 00:28:39.906 A:middle
SpriteKit and SceneKit are great

00:28:39.946 --> 00:28:41.206 A:middle
for building custom UI.

00:28:41.666 --> 00:28:42.806 A:middle
They're not just for building

00:28:43.536 --> 00:28:44.106 A:middle
games.

00:28:44.736 --> 00:28:47.166 A:middle
As an example, on the Xcode Team

00:28:47.166 --> 00:28:48.906 A:middle
we use these frameworks to build

00:28:48.906 --> 00:28:49.936 A:middle
our visual debuggers.

00:28:50.686 --> 00:28:52.836 A:middle
This is an example of the Memory

00:28:52.836 --> 00:28:53.626 A:middle
Graph Debugger that we

00:28:53.626 --> 00:28:54.626 A:middle
introduced last year.

00:28:55.266 --> 00:28:57.236 A:middle
It's showing a memory graph for

00:28:57.236 --> 00:28:58.236 A:middle
an app running on an iPhone.

00:28:59.516 --> 00:29:01.726 A:middle
Now, that visual memory graph,

00:29:02.336 --> 00:29:03.756 A:middle
we built that using SpriteKit.

00:29:04.166 --> 00:29:05.436 A:middle
So now we're really excited that

00:29:05.436 --> 00:29:06.816 A:middle
we can use our new SpriteKit

00:29:07.146 --> 00:29:08.576 A:middle
Debugger to debug our Memory

00:29:08.576 --> 00:29:09.076 A:middle
Graph Debugger.

00:29:09.896 --> 00:29:10.886 A:middle
Let me show you how that would

00:29:11.766 --> 00:29:11.896 A:middle
work.

00:29:12.396 --> 00:29:13.796 A:middle
Let's bring in another Xcode to

00:29:13.796 --> 00:29:15.536 A:middle
debug this first Xcode

00:29:15.556 --> 00:29:17.556 A:middle
[laughter].

00:29:17.576 --> 00:29:19.046 A:middle
It's taken a snapshot of that

00:29:19.046 --> 00:29:20.446 A:middle
view hierarchy and it now

00:29:20.446 --> 00:29:22.286 A:middle
includes all of the Sprites that

00:29:22.286 --> 00:29:23.856 A:middle
were shown as part of the Memory

00:29:23.856 --> 00:29:24.336 A:middle
Graph Debugger.

00:29:24.836 --> 00:29:26.286 A:middle
We can select an option to show

00:29:26.286 --> 00:29:27.376 A:middle
all the clip's content.

00:29:27.376 --> 00:29:28.336 A:middle
So now we can see all the

00:29:28.336 --> 00:29:29.316 A:middle
Sprites that are outside the

00:29:29.316 --> 00:29:30.306 A:middle
visible region.

00:29:30.306 --> 00:29:32.576 A:middle
And we can continue to zoom out

00:29:32.576 --> 00:29:34.276 A:middle
to get a big picture view of

00:29:34.276 --> 00:29:36.296 A:middle
that entire scene, a SpriteKit

00:29:36.356 --> 00:29:36.636 A:middle
scene.

00:29:37.326 --> 00:29:40.086 A:middle
So that's an example.

00:29:40.086 --> 00:29:41.456 A:middle
And this is actually what we do

00:29:41.456 --> 00:29:42.276 A:middle
on the Xcode Team.

00:29:42.536 --> 00:29:43.646 A:middle
We use our debuggers to debug

00:29:43.646 --> 00:29:43.976 A:middle
other debuggers.

00:29:44.516 --> 00:29:47.746 A:middle
[ Laughter ]

00:29:48.246 --> 00:29:50.956 A:middle
Now, to make these view

00:29:50.956 --> 00:29:52.286 A:middle
hierarchies exploded out in this

00:29:52.286 --> 00:29:56.286 A:middle
custom 3D visualization we used

00:29:56.386 --> 00:29:56.886 A:middle
SceneKit.

00:29:57.406 --> 00:29:58.946 A:middle
And so now we're doubly excited

00:29:58.946 --> 00:30:00.336 A:middle
that we can use our new SceneKit

00:30:00.336 --> 00:30:01.886 A:middle
Debugger to debug our View

00:30:01.886 --> 00:30:02.196 A:middle
Debugger.

00:30:02.996 --> 00:30:03.946 A:middle
Who wants to see that?

00:30:05.016 --> 00:30:06.926 A:middle
Let's bring in another Xcode to

00:30:06.926 --> 00:30:07.696 A:middle
debug the previous Xcode.

00:30:08.516 --> 00:30:10.516 A:middle
[ Laughter ]

00:30:11.516 --> 00:30:17.466 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:30:17.966 --> 00:30:18.976 A:middle
So it's taken a snapshot of the

00:30:18.976 --> 00:30:20.176 A:middle
view hierarchy and exploded it

00:30:20.176 --> 00:30:22.476 A:middle
out in 3D, but now, because it's

00:30:22.476 --> 00:30:23.946 A:middle
Xcode 9, we have access to that

00:30:23.946 --> 00:30:24.826 A:middle
SceneKit scene.

00:30:24.886 --> 00:30:26.916 A:middle
So we can select that and we can

00:30:26.916 --> 00:30:29.256 A:middle
view that 3D custom

00:30:29.426 --> 00:30:30.726 A:middle
visualization in the SceneKit

00:30:30.726 --> 00:30:31.136 A:middle
Editor.

00:30:31.906 --> 00:30:33.576 A:middle
We can change cameras, change

00:30:33.576 --> 00:30:35.566 A:middle
perspectives to find the 3D

00:30:35.566 --> 00:30:36.646 A:middle
object in the scene that we're

00:30:36.646 --> 00:30:37.386 A:middle
looking to debug.

00:30:37.386 --> 00:30:40.936 A:middle
So that's the kind of fun we

00:30:40.936 --> 00:30:41.696 A:middle
have in Xcode.

00:30:43.306 --> 00:30:44.936 A:middle
So that's an example, what I've

00:30:44.936 --> 00:30:46.606 A:middle
shown you is an example of using

00:30:46.606 --> 00:30:49.416 A:middle
the new -- Xcode's new SceneKit

00:30:49.536 --> 00:30:51.966 A:middle
Debugger to debug the Xcode View

00:30:51.966 --> 00:30:53.286 A:middle
Debugger visualization, which

00:30:53.286 --> 00:30:55.416 A:middle
itself was SpriteKit debugging

00:30:55.676 --> 00:30:56.866 A:middle
the Memory Graph Debugger, which

00:30:56.866 --> 00:30:58.566 A:middle
itself was Memory Graph

00:30:58.566 --> 00:30:59.796 A:middle
debugging an app on the iPhone.

00:31:00.336 --> 00:31:01.706 A:middle
If you can follow along with all

00:31:01.706 --> 00:31:02.426 A:middle
that, then maybe you've got a

00:31:02.426 --> 00:31:02.976 A:middle
future on the Xcode Team

00:31:03.016 --> 00:31:03.516 A:middle
[ Laughter ]

00:31:03.516 --> 00:31:04.016 A:middle
.

00:31:04.516 --> 00:31:10.456 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:31:10.956 --> 00:31:12.546 A:middle
Now, to give you a demonstration

00:31:12.546 --> 00:31:13.586 A:middle
of these new view debugging

00:31:13.586 --> 00:31:14.916 A:middle
enhancements, I'd like to invite

00:31:14.916 --> 00:31:15.486 A:middle
up Sebastian.

00:31:15.486 --> 00:31:15.956 A:middle
Thank you.

00:31:16.516 --> 00:31:20.096 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:31:20.596 --> 00:31:21.236 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Thanks, Chris.

00:31:22.226 --> 00:31:22.856 A:middle
That's awesome.

00:31:23.556 --> 00:31:24.786 A:middle
I'm excited to show you some of

00:31:24.846 --> 00:31:26.206 A:middle
the new enhancements we made to

00:31:26.206 --> 00:31:27.996 A:middle
debugging in Xcode 9, but I'll

00:31:27.996 --> 00:31:29.826 A:middle
be using a slightly less complex

00:31:29.826 --> 00:31:30.916 A:middle
example than Chris just showed

00:31:30.916 --> 00:31:30.983 A:middle
you.

00:31:36.116 --> 00:31:37.416 A:middle
I'll actually be using the same

00:31:37.596 --> 00:31:38.746 A:middle
iOS app that Breckin used

00:31:38.746 --> 00:31:40.416 A:middle
earlier for his application, for

00:31:40.416 --> 00:31:42.246 A:middle
his demonstration, and it's

00:31:42.246 --> 00:31:45.426 A:middle
showing the solar system when

00:31:46.696 --> 00:31:47.846 A:middle
you launch the app, and it's

00:31:47.846 --> 00:31:49.106 A:middle
starting off with a 3D

00:31:49.106 --> 00:31:49.946 A:middle
visualization.

00:31:50.466 --> 00:31:51.746 A:middle
Now, using the button in the top

00:31:51.746 --> 00:31:53.396 A:middle
right corner the user can get

00:31:53.396 --> 00:31:56.306 A:middle
additional details about the

00:31:56.526 --> 00:31:58.276 A:middle
planets, and I've been working

00:31:58.276 --> 00:31:59.356 A:middle
on a very cool feature here.

00:31:59.736 --> 00:32:00.976 A:middle
My idea was to let the user

00:32:00.976 --> 00:32:03.256 A:middle
experience the gravity on the

00:32:03.256 --> 00:32:04.996 A:middle
different planets, so I built a

00:32:04.996 --> 00:32:06.296 A:middle
gravitySimulator using

00:32:06.296 --> 00:32:06.906 A:middle
SpriteKit.

00:32:07.136 --> 00:32:08.216 A:middle
Let me show you what that looks

00:32:08.216 --> 00:32:08.446 A:middle
like.

00:32:09.596 --> 00:32:11.436 A:middle
The gravitySimulator starts off

00:32:11.436 --> 00:32:13.116 A:middle
in zero gravity and the three

00:32:13.116 --> 00:32:14.746 A:middle
objects hover around in space.

00:32:15.196 --> 00:32:16.456 A:middle
Now, when the user swipes down

00:32:16.456 --> 00:32:18.446 A:middle
on the device's display, gravity

00:32:18.446 --> 00:32:19.736 A:middle
is activated and the three

00:32:19.736 --> 00:32:21.226 A:middle
objects begin to fall and

00:32:21.226 --> 00:32:22.396 A:middle
eventually hit the bottom of the

00:32:22.396 --> 00:32:23.416 A:middle
screen and bounce around.

00:32:24.096 --> 00:32:25.176 A:middle
Unfortunately, I got a bug

00:32:25.176 --> 00:32:26.316 A:middle
report that it's not behaving

00:32:26.316 --> 00:32:26.766 A:middle
quite right.

00:32:27.266 --> 00:32:28.546 A:middle
So let me swipe down and let's

00:32:28.546 --> 00:32:32.076 A:middle
observe what is going on.

00:32:32.076 --> 00:32:34.346 A:middle
Oh, now I understand what the

00:32:34.346 --> 00:32:35.276 A:middle
user was talking about.

00:32:35.786 --> 00:32:36.946 A:middle
So it looks like the gravity is

00:32:36.946 --> 00:32:38.796 A:middle
activated correctly, but the

00:32:38.796 --> 00:32:39.946 A:middle
objects don't actually hit the

00:32:39.946 --> 00:32:41.466 A:middle
bottom of the screen and bounce

00:32:41.466 --> 00:32:42.916 A:middle
around, they just go off screen.

00:32:43.506 --> 00:32:44.476 A:middle
Let's see if we can use the View

00:32:44.476 --> 00:32:45.586 A:middle
Debugger to better understand

00:32:45.586 --> 00:32:47.146 A:middle
what is going on here and try to

00:32:47.146 --> 00:32:47.966 A:middle
address the problem.

00:32:49.396 --> 00:32:50.376 A:middle
I'll invoke the View Debugger

00:32:50.376 --> 00:32:51.856 A:middle
using the button in the Debug

00:32:51.856 --> 00:32:54.826 A:middle
bar, and Xcode now fetches the

00:32:54.826 --> 00:32:56.866 A:middle
entire view hierarchy, including

00:32:56.866 --> 00:32:58.316 A:middle
the content of all SpriteKit

00:32:58.316 --> 00:32:59.436 A:middle
scenes that are part of the view

00:32:59.436 --> 00:32:59.896 A:middle
hierarchy.

00:33:00.476 --> 00:33:01.826 A:middle
On the left-hand side you get an

00:33:01.826 --> 00:33:03.046 A:middle
outline representation of that

00:33:03.046 --> 00:33:04.416 A:middle
hierarchy; whereas, in the

00:33:04.416 --> 00:33:05.486 A:middle
center you get a visual

00:33:05.486 --> 00:33:06.396 A:middle
representation.

00:33:07.276 --> 00:33:08.466 A:middle
Now, as you can see, the View

00:33:08.466 --> 00:33:09.746 A:middle
Debugger matches exactly what

00:33:09.746 --> 00:33:11.086 A:middle
you see on the device's display,

00:33:11.516 --> 00:33:12.626 A:middle
and you may be wondering how is

00:33:12.676 --> 00:33:14.216 A:middle
that particularly useful in this

00:33:14.216 --> 00:33:14.576 A:middle
case.

00:33:15.566 --> 00:33:17.006 A:middle
Now, if we recap what happened,

00:33:17.196 --> 00:33:18.576 A:middle
the three objects, they went off

00:33:18.576 --> 00:33:20.726 A:middle
screen, and by default the View

00:33:20.726 --> 00:33:22.096 A:middle
Debugger only shows you objects

00:33:22.096 --> 00:33:22.776 A:middle
that are visible.

00:33:23.436 --> 00:33:25.076 A:middle
Now, we can use this button here

00:33:25.186 --> 00:33:27.666 A:middle
in the bottom left corner to

00:33:27.666 --> 00:33:28.856 A:middle
also show content that is

00:33:28.896 --> 00:33:29.726 A:middle
currently being clipped.

00:33:30.366 --> 00:33:31.176 A:middle
So we can see that there's

00:33:31.176 --> 00:33:32.406 A:middle
actually a lot more going on

00:33:32.406 --> 00:33:33.356 A:middle
here than we can see on the

00:33:33.356 --> 00:33:34.236 A:middle
device's display.

00:33:34.996 --> 00:33:36.066 A:middle
Let me zoom out a little bit so

00:33:36.066 --> 00:33:37.946 A:middle
we can get a better overview.

00:33:38.396 --> 00:33:39.816 A:middle
And we actually found our three

00:33:39.816 --> 00:33:40.656 A:middle
objects down here.

00:33:41.306 --> 00:33:42.976 A:middle
So it looks like what's going on

00:33:43.686 --> 00:33:45.046 A:middle
is that the SpriteKit scene is

00:33:45.046 --> 00:33:46.556 A:middle
just too tall for the device's

00:33:46.556 --> 00:33:48.386 A:middle
display and by the time they hit

00:33:48.386 --> 00:33:49.256 A:middle
the bottom of the scene and

00:33:49.256 --> 00:33:50.646 A:middle
bounce around, they're already

00:33:50.646 --> 00:33:51.236 A:middle
off screen.

00:33:52.536 --> 00:33:53.726 A:middle
So let's see if we can address

00:33:53.726 --> 00:33:54.336 A:middle
this problem.

00:33:54.966 --> 00:33:56.416 A:middle
I'll select the SpriteKit scene

00:33:56.416 --> 00:33:57.426 A:middle
in the Debug Navigator on the

00:33:57.426 --> 00:33:58.916 A:middle
left-hand side and let's take a

00:33:58.916 --> 00:34:00.426 A:middle
look at its properties and see

00:34:00.426 --> 00:34:01.546 A:middle
if we can find one that we can

00:34:01.546 --> 00:34:01.946 A:middle
act on.

00:34:02.306 --> 00:34:03.936 A:middle
So you can see that we can get

00:34:03.936 --> 00:34:05.936 A:middle
additional details about the

00:34:05.936 --> 00:34:07.466 A:middle
SpriteKit scene's size, it's

00:34:07.466 --> 00:34:09.706 A:middle
anchor point and it's scaleMode.

00:34:10.336 --> 00:34:11.656 A:middle
Now, the scaleMode is currently

00:34:11.656 --> 00:34:12.796 A:middle
set to Aspect Fill and that

00:34:12.796 --> 00:34:14.036 A:middle
looks a little bit suspicious.

00:34:14.476 --> 00:34:15.666 A:middle
I think there is a better aspect

00:34:15.666 --> 00:34:17.026 A:middle
fill to achieve what we're

00:34:17.196 --> 00:34:20.416 A:middle
trying to -- what we want the

00:34:20.416 --> 00:34:21.066 A:middle
scene to behave.

00:34:21.106 --> 00:34:22.596 A:middle
We want it to resize to actually

00:34:22.596 --> 00:34:23.746 A:middle
fit the device's display.

00:34:25.246 --> 00:34:26.736 A:middle
Now, I'm setting up the entire

00:34:26.736 --> 00:34:28.286 A:middle
SpriteKit scene in the hosting

00:34:28.286 --> 00:34:29.826 A:middle
View Controller, and since the

00:34:29.826 --> 00:34:30.706 A:middle
view controllers are now

00:34:30.706 --> 00:34:31.876 A:middle
presented right along the view

00:34:31.876 --> 00:34:33.496 A:middle
hierarchy, it's very easy to get

00:34:33.496 --> 00:34:33.846 A:middle
to them.

00:34:34.586 --> 00:34:36.106 A:middle
I can simply select the

00:34:36.196 --> 00:34:37.676 A:middle
gravitySimulator View Controller

00:34:37.676 --> 00:34:38.756 A:middle
and the Debug Navigator on the

00:34:38.756 --> 00:34:40.676 A:middle
left-hand side, and using the

00:34:40.676 --> 00:34:42.076 A:middle
Inspector on the right-hand side

00:34:42.336 --> 00:34:43.696 A:middle
it's very easy to jump right to

00:34:43.696 --> 00:34:44.546 A:middle
the implementation.

00:34:45.106 --> 00:34:47.576 A:middle
I can use this button here that

00:34:47.576 --> 00:34:48.976 A:middle
is right next to the Class Name,

00:34:49.816 --> 00:34:50.806 A:middle
and we're here in the

00:34:50.806 --> 00:34:52.126 A:middle
implementation of this class.

00:34:53.326 --> 00:34:54.366 A:middle
And I'm setting up a couple of

